# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: armillaria-mellea
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:armillaria-mellea/adalbert-ricken] He attended the seminary for Roman Catholic priests in Fulda, and afterwards was a priest and chaplain at several locations in the Fulda diocese.
[src:armillaria-mellea/adalbert-ricken] He made contributions in the classification of fungi, and was the author of a popular textbook on mushrooms called *Vademecum für Pilzfreunde* (Digital edition by the University and State Library Düsseldorf).
[src:armillaria-mellea/adalbert-ricken] Another noted work by Ricken was *Die Blätterpilze (Agaricaceae) Deutschlands und der angrenzenden Länder, besonders Oesterreichs und der Schweiz* (1915), a publication on fungi from the family Agaricaceae that are native to central Europe.
[src:armillaria-mellea/adalbert-ricken] The genus *Rickenella* from the family Repetobasidiaceae is named in his honor.
[src:armillaria-mellea/adalbert-ricken] Since 1987, the "Adalbert Ricken Preis" is awarded by the *Deutsche Gesellschaft für Mykologie* for research done by young amateur mycologists.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] The genus ***Aesculus*** (/ˈaɪskjʊləs/) is a genus of flowering plants in the family Sapindaceae.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] They are trees and shrubs, mostly native to the temperate Northern Hemisphere, but one species (*A. assamica*) into subtropical areas of southeast Asia.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] The Plants of the World Online (POWO) database currently accepts 12 species, with seven species native to North America, four native to Asia, and one native to Europe; some other authors have accepted more species.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] Hardin (1957–1960) accepted 13 species, the *Trees and Shrubs Online* website cites "13–15" species with descriptions given for 14 species, and Harris et al.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] Six natural hybrids occur, and several others have been raised in cultivation.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] The European and Asian species are known as **horse-chestnut** or **horse chestnut**, and the North American species as **buckeye**.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] *Aesculus* exhibits a classical Arcto-Tertiary distribution.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] Carl Linnaeus named the genus *Aesculus* after the Roman name for an edible acorn.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] The genus was considered to be in the ditypic family Hippocastanaceae along with *Billia*, but phylogenetic analyses of morphological and molecular data have more recently caused this family, along with the Aceraceae (maples and *Dipteronia*), to be included in the soapberry family (Sapindaceae).
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] The fruit of the Mexican buckeye resemble *Aesculus* fruit, but belong to a related though different genus *Ungnadia*.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] The common name "horse chestnut" invites confusion with the chestnuts in the genus *Castanea* in the order Fagales; the name is often hyphenated as horse-chestnut to minimise this confusion.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] All parts of the trees are moderately toxic, but the attractive nut-like seeds are the most likely part to cause poisoning.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] The toxin affects the gastrointestinal system, causing gastrointestinal disturbances.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] The USDA notes that the toxicity is due to the saponin aescin and the glucoside aesculin, with alkaloids possibly contributing.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] In North America, several native American tribes, particularly in the western and central United States, such as Miwok, Pomo, Yokut, Maidu, historically used buckeye seeds like California buckeye to harvest fish by using the saponins, which had been extracted by the plant's seeds.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] These tribes would crush buckeye seeds to release saponins into streams or shallow water, where the compounds would stun or kill the fish, allowing for easier capture.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] They then boiled and drained (leached) the fish at least three times to dilute the toxin's effects.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] New shoots from the seeds also have been known to kill grazing cattle.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] In Britain, the fruit are often called **conkers** because of their link to the game of conkers, played with the seeds.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] The most familiar member of the genus worldwide is the common horse-chestnut, *Aesculus hippocastanum*.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] The yellow buckeye, *Aesculus flava* (syn.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] *A. octandra*), is also a valuable ornamental tree with yellow flowers, but is less widely planted.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] Among the smaller species is the bottlebrush buckeye, *Aesculus parviflora*, a flowering shrub.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] Several other members of the genus are used as ornamental plants, and several horticultural hybrids have also been developed, most notably the red horse-chestnut *Aesculus* × *carnea*, a hybrid between *A. hippocastanum* and *A. pavia*.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] The horse-chestnut *A. hippocastanum* was unknown to botanical science until 1596, when the Dutch botanist Carolus Clusius was given foliage and flowers in Vienna; it was then introduced further west, with the first plants reaching France in 1603, and Britain between 1612–1615.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] In Geneva, Switzerland, an official chestnut tree is used to indicate the beginning of the Spring; every year since 1818, the tree is observed by the secretary of the Grand Council of Geneva (the local parliament), and the opening of the first leaf is recorded and announced publicly.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] Over the years, four different horse chestnut trees have been used for these recordings.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] In the 1840 U.S. presidential campaign, candidate William Henry Harrison called himself the "log cabin and hard cider candidate", portraying himself sitting in a log cabin made of buckeye logs and drinking hard cider, causing Ohio to become known as "the Buckeye State".
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] The leaf of *Aesculus* was the official symbol of Kyiv on its coat of arms used from 1969 to 1995.
[src:armillaria-mellea/aesculus] It remains an official symbol of Kyiv to this day.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricales] The **Agaricales** are an order of fungi in the division Basidiomycota.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricales] As originally conceived, the order contained all the agarics (gilled mushrooms), but subsequent research has shown that not all agarics are closely related and some belong in other orders, such as the Russulales and Boletales.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricales] Conversely, DNA research has also shown that many non-agarics, including some of the clavarioid fungi (clubs and corals) and gasteroid fungi (puffballs and false truffles) belong within the Agaricales.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricales] The order has 46 extant families, more than 400 genera, and over 25,000 described species, along with six extinct genera known only from the fossil record.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricales] Species in the Agaricales range from the familiar *Agaricus bisporus* (cultivated mushroom) and the deadly *Amanita virosa* (destroying angel) to the coral-like *Clavaria zollingeri* (violet coral) and bracket-like *Fistulina hepatica* (beefsteak fungus).
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricales] In his three volumes of *Systema Mycologicum* published between 1821 and 1832, Elias Fries put almost all of the fleshy, gill-forming mushrooms in the genus *Agaricus*.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricales] He organized the large genus into "tribes", the names of many of which still exist as common genera of today.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricales] Fries later elevated several of these tribes to generic level, but later authors—including Gillet, Karsten, Kummer, Quélet, and Staude—made most of the changes.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricales] Fries based his classification on macroscopic characters of the fruit bodies and color of the spore print.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricales] His system had been widely used as it had the advantage that many genera could be readily identified based on characters observable in the field.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricales] Fries's classification was later challenged when microscopic studies of basidiocarp structure, initiated by Fayod and Patouillard, demonstrated several of Fries's groupings were unnatural.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricales] Singer treated three major groups within the Agaricales *sensu lato*: the Agaricales *sensu stricto*, Boletineae, and Russulales.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricales] These groups are still accepted by modern treatments based on DNA analysis, as the euagarics clade, bolete clade, and russuloid clade.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricales] Molecular phylogenetics research has demonstrated that the euagarics clade is roughly equivalent to Singer's Agaricales *sensu stricto*.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricales] A large-scale study by Brandon Matheny and colleagues used nucleic acid sequences representing six gene regions from 238 species in 146 genera to explore the phylogenetic grouping within the Agaricales.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricales] The analysis showed that most of the species tested could be grouped into six clades that were named the Agaricoid, Tricholomatoid, Marasmioid, Pluteoid, Hygrophoroid and Plicaturopsidoid clades.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricales] Molecular studies have shown that agarics are more divergent than once thought.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricales] Agarics in the genera *Russula* and *Lactarius*, for example, belong to the order Russulales, whilst agarics in the genera *Paxillus* and *Hygrophoropsis* belong in the Boletales.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricales] Conversely some genera with non-agaric fruit bodies, such as the puffballs, bird's nest fungi, and many clavarioid fungi, belong in the Agaricales.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricales] Members of the Agaricales are ubiquitous, with species found in all continents.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricales] The great majority are terrestrial, in almost every habitat from woodland and grassland to deserts and dunes.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricales] Agaricoid species were long thought to be solely terrestrial, until the 2005 discovery of *Psathyrella aquatica*, the only gilled mushroom known to fruit underwater.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricales] Species are variously saprotrophic or ectomycorrhizal, occasionally parasitic on plants or other fungi, and sometimes lichenized.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricales] the Agaricales include six monotypic fossil genera mostly found fossilized in amber.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricales] The three other species, *Aureofungus yaniguaensis*, *Coprinites dominicana* and *Protomycena electra* are known from single specimens found in the Dominican amber mines of Hispaniola.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricomycetes] The **Agaricomycetes** are a class of fungi in the division Basidiomycota.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricomycetes] The taxon is roughly identical to that defined for the **Homobasidiomycetes** (alternatively called holobasidiomycetes) by Hibbett & Thorn, with the inclusion of Auriculariales and Sebacinales.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricomycetes] It includes not only mushroom-forming fungi, but also most species placed in the deprecated taxa Gasteromycetes and Homobasidiomycetes.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricomycetes] Within the subdivision Agaricomycotina, which already excludes the smut and rust fungi, the Agaricomycetes can be further defined by the exclusion of the classes Tremellomycetes and Dacrymycetes, which are generally considered to be jelly fungi.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricomycetes] However, a few former "jelly fungi", such as *Auricularia*, are classified in the Agaricomycetes.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricomycetes] According to a 2008 estimate, Agaricomycetes include 17 orders, 100 families, 1147 genera, and about 21000 species.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricomycetes] Modern molecular phylogenetic analyses have been since used to help define several new orders in the Agaricomycetes: Amylocorticiales, Jaapiales, Stereopsidales, and Lepidostromatales.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricomycetes] Although morphology of the mushroom or fruit body (basidiocarp) was the basis of early classification of the Agaricomycetes, this is no longer the case.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricomycetes] As an example, the distinction between the *Gasteromycetes* (including puffballs) and *Agaricomycetes* (most other agaric mushrooms) is no longer recognized as a natural one—various puffball species have apparently evolved independently from agaricomycete fungi.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricomycetes] However, most mushroom guide books still group the puffballs or gasteroid forms separate from other mushrooms because the older Friesian classification is still convenient for categorizing fruit body forms.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricomycetes] Similarly, modern classifications divide the gasteroid order Lycoperdales between Agaricales and Phallales.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricomycetes] All members of the class produce basidiocarps which range in size from tiny cups a few millimeters across to a giant polypore (*Phellinus ellipsoideus*) greater than several meters across and weigh up to 500 kilograms (1,100 lb).
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricomycetes] The group also includes what are arguably the largest and oldest individual organisms on earth: the mycelium of one individual *Armillaria gallica* has been estimated to extend over 15 hectares (37 acres) with a mass of 10,000 kilograms (22,000 pounds) and an age of 1,500 years.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricomycetes] Agaricomycetes also have antibacterial properties.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricomycetes] Agaricomycetes can help in research in treating bacteria.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricomycetes] Nearly all species are terrestrial (a few are aquatic), occurring in a wide range of environments where most function as decayers, especially of wood.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricomycetes] However, some species are pathogenic or parasitic, and yet others are symbiotic (i.e., mutualistic), these including the important ectomycorrhizal symbionts of forest trees.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricomycetes] General discussions on the forms and life cycles of these fungi are developed in the article on mushrooms, in the treatments of the various orders (links in table at right), and in individual species accounts.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricomycetes] The fruit bodies of Agaricomycetes are extremely rare in the fossil record, and the class does not yet pre-date the Early Cretaceous (146–100 Ma).
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricomycetes] The oldest Agaricomycetes fossil, dating from the lower Cretaceous (130–125 Ma) is *Quatsinoporites*.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricomycetes] It is a fragment of a poroid fruit body with features that suggest it could be a member of the family Hymenochaetaceae.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricomycetes] Based on molecular clock analysis, the Agaricomycetes are estimated to be about 290 million years old.
[src:armillaria-mellea/agaricomycetes] There are many genera in the Agaricomycetes that have not been classified in any order or family.
[src:armillaria-mellea/annulus-mycology] An **annulus** is the ring-like or collar-like structure sometimes found on the stipe of some species of mushrooms.
[src:armillaria-mellea/annulus-mycology] The annulus represents the remnants of the partial veil, after it has ruptured to expose the gills or other spore-producing surface.
[src:armillaria-mellea/annulus-mycology] It can also be called a **ring** which is what the Latin word annulus directly translates as.
[src:armillaria-mellea/annulus-mycology] The modern usage of the Latin word originates from the early days of botany and mycology when species descriptions were only written in Latin.
[src:armillaria-mellea/annulus-mycology] Outside of the formal setting of scientific publications which still have a Latin requirement, it will often just be referred to as a ring or stem ring in field guides and on identification websites.
[src:armillaria-mellea/annulus-mycology] The way in which the structure and appearance of rings is described can vary with author and the description may only note the existence of a ring without providing specific information in cases where the ring lacks any notable features that would be useful to distinguish between similar species.
[src:armillaria-mellea/annulus-mycology] Ring shapes and structures can also vary between specimens of the same species and change with the age of the mushroom so multiple descriptions are sometimes used.
[src:armillaria-mellea/annulus-mycology] Even in species with distinctly identifiable rings they may not always be present or perfectly match descriptions so it can be beneficial to have multiple specimens to compare at different states of maturity.
[src:armillaria-mellea/annulus-mycology] Some rings may be persistent and remain through the life of the mushroom or they may disappear with age.
[src:armillaria-mellea/annulus-mycology] Such rings have a variety of synonymous terms associated with them such as fleeting, ephemeral, evanescent, transient, fugacious or impermanent.
[src:armillaria-mellea/annulus-mycology] These rings may peel away from the stem, fall apart or simply fade into the stem surface as it matures.
[src:armillaria-mellea/annulus-mycology] Rings may also be described as fragile, meaning easily torn or damaged and whilst some fragile rings could be considered permanent if undisturbed they are often likely to vanish due to their fragility.
[src:armillaria-mellea/annulus-mycology] Some rings may be fixed in place and firmly attached to the stem whilst others may be movable or mobile with the ability to slide up and down the stem either by hand or just falling down naturally with age.
[src:armillaria-mellea/annulus-mycology] Fragile and movable rings can appear to vanish so examining the stem for traces of a ring zone (or annular zone) or the base for a detached ring can sometimes be helpful.
[src:armillaria-mellea/annulus-mycology] Various combinations of these terms can be used to best describe the nature of the ring in a particular species.
[src:armillaria-mellea/annulus-mycology] The texture of the partial veil can exhibit specific characteristics which can aid in identification and these may persist in the ring once the cap has detached from it.
[src:armillaria-mellea/annulus-mycology] These details may be similar to that of the cap surface or distinct from it.
[src:armillaria-mellea/annulus-mycology] The position of the ring can be an important factor to observe to aid in identification although it is often not included in descriptions as for some species it can be quite variable.
[src:armillaria-mellea/annulus-mycology] The position may appear different from specimen to specimen due to the height of the stem or the age of the mushroom and in species with movable, fragile or otherwise detachable rings it may not always be a reliable factor to observe.
[src:armillaria-mellea/annulus-mycology] However for species which otherwise look quite similar but exhibit differences in colouration, texture or staining above or below the stem ring, the position can be a useful factor to note.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] Confusion has surrounded the nomenclature and taxonomy of the species now known as *Armillaria gallica*, paralleling that surrounding the genus *Armillaria*.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] The type species, *Armillaria mellea*, was until the 1970s believed to be a pleiomorphic species with a wide distribution, variable pathogenicity, and one of the broadest host ranges known for the fungi.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] In 1973, Veikko Hintikka reported a technique to distinguish between *Armillaria* species by growing them together as single spore isolates on petri dishes and observing changes in the morphology of the cultures.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] Using a similar technique, Kari Korhonen showed in 1978 that the European *Armillaria mellea* species complex could be separated into five reproductively isolated species, which he named "European Biological Species" (EBS) A through E.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] About the same time, the North American *A. mellea* was shown to be ten different species (North American Biological Species, or NABS I through X); NABS VII was demonstrated shortly after to be the same species as EBS E.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] Because several research groups had worked with this widely distributed species, it was assigned several different names.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] The species that Korhonen called EBS B was named *A. bulbosa* by Helga Marxmüller in 1982, as it was thought to be equivalent to *Armillaria mellea* var.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] *bulbosa*, first described by Jean Baptiste Barla (Joseph Barla) in 1887, and later raised to species status by Josef Velenovský in 1927.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] In 1973, the French mycologist Henri Romagnesi, unaware of Velenovský's publication, published a description of the species he called *Armillariella bulbosa*, based on specimens he had found near Compiègne and Saint-Sauveur-le-Vicomte in France.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] These specimens were later demonstrated to be the same species as the EBS E of Korhonen; EBS B was later determined to be *A. cepistipes*.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] Therefore, the name *A. bulbosa* was a misapplied name for EBS E.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] In 1987 Romagnesi and Marxmüller renamed EBS E to *Armillaria gallica*.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] Another synonym, *A. lutea*, had originally been described by Claude Casimir Gillet in 1874, and proposed as a name for EBS E.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] Although the name had priority due to its early publication date, it was rejected as a *nomen ambiguum* because of a lack of supporting evidence to identify the fungus, including a specimen, type locality, and incomplete collection notes.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] *A. inflata* (Velenovský, 1920) may represent another synonym, but the type specimens were not preserved, so it is considered a dubious name (*nomen dubium*).
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] As of 2010, both the Index Fungorum and MycoBank consider *Armillaria gallica* Marxm. & Romagn. to be the current name, with *A. bulbosa* and *A. lutea* as synonyms.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] Phylogenetic analysis of North American *Armillaria* species based on analysis of amplified fragment length polymorphism data suggests that *A. gallica* is most closely related to *A. sinapina*, *A. cepistipes*, and *A. calvescens*.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] These results are similar to those reported in 1992 that compared sequences of nuclear ribosomal DNA.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] The specific epithet *gallica* is botanical Latin for "French" (from *Gallia*, "Gaul"), and refers to the type locality.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] The prior name *bulbosa* is Latin for "bulb-bearing, bulbous" (from *bulbus* and the suffix -*osa*).
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] *Armillaria* is derived from the Latin *armilla*, or "bracelet".
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] Young fruit bodies have a cottony partial veil that protects the developing gills.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] The fruit bodies of *Armillaria gallica* have caps that are 2.5–9.5 cm (1.0–3.7 in) broad, and depending on their age, may range in shape from conical to convex to flattened.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] The caps are brownish-yellow to brown when moist, often with a darker-colored center; the color tends to fade upon drying.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] The cap surface is covered with slender fibers (same color as the cap) that are erect, or sloping upwards.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] When the fruit bodies are young, the underside of the caps have a cottony layer of tissue stretching from the edge of the cap to the stem—a partial veil—which serves to protect the developing gills.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] As the cap grows in size the membrane is eventually pulled away from the cap to expose the gills.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] The gills have an adnate (squarely attached) to somewhat decurrent (extending down the length of the stem) attachment to the stem.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] They are initially white, but age to a creamy or pale orange covered with rust-colored spots.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] Above the level of the ring, the stem is pale orange to brown, while below it is whitish or pale pink, becoming grayish-brown at the base.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] The ring is positioned about 0.4–0.9 cm (0.16–0.35 in) below the level of the cap, and may be covered with yellowish to pale-brownish woolly cottony mycelia.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] The base of the stem is attached to rhizomorphs, black root-like structures 1–3 mm in diameter.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] While the primary function of the below-ground mycelia is to absorb nutrients from the soil, the rhizomorphs serve a more exploratory function, to locate new food bases.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] When the spores are seen in deposit, such as with a spore print, they appear whitish.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] They have an ellipsoid or oblong shape, usually contain an oil droplet, and have dimensions of 7–8.5 by 5–6 μm.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] The spore-bearing cells, the basidia, are club-shaped, four-spored (rarely two-spored), and measure 32–43 by 7–8.7 μm.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] Other cells present in the fertile hymenium include the cheilocystidia (cystidia present on the edge of a gill), which are club-shaped, roughly cylindrical and 15–25 by 5.0–12 μm.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] Cystidia are also present on the stem (called caulocystidia), and are broadly club-shaped, measuring 20–55 by 11–23 μm.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] The cap cuticle is made of hyphae that are irregularly interwoven and project upward to form the scales seen on the surface.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] The hyphae that make up the surface scales typically measure 26–88 μm long by 11–27 μm thick and can be covered with a crust of pigment.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] Clamp connections are present in the hyphae of most tissues.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] Like all *Armillaria* species, *A. gallica* is considered edible.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] Thorough cooking is usually recommended, as the raw mushroom tastes acrid when fresh or undercooked.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] One author advises to consume only a small portion initially, as some people may experience an upset stomach.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] The taste is described as "mild to bitter", and the odor "sweet", or reminiscent of camembert cheese.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] The mycelia and fruiting bodies of *Armillaria gallica* are known to be bioluminescent.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] Experiments have shown that the intensity of the luminescence is enhanced when the mycelia are disturbed during growth.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] Bioluminescence is caused by the action of luciferases, enzymes that produce light by the oxidation of a luciferin (a pigment).
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] In one particular forest stand, *Armillaria*-infected oak trees had been harvested, and their stumps were left to rot in the field.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] Later, when red pines were planted in the same location, the seedlings were killed by the fungus, identified as *A. gallica* (then known as *A. bulbosa*).
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] Using molecular genetics, they determined that the underground mycelia of one individual fungal colony covered 15 ha (37 acres), weighing over 9,500 kilograms (21,000 lb), with an estimated age of 1,500 years.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] In their conclusion, the authors noted: "This is the first report estimating the minimum size, mass, and age of an unambiguously defined fungal individual.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] There was afterward some scholarly debate as to whether the fungus qualified to be considered in the same category as other large organisms such as the blue whale or the giant redwood.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] The fungus has since become a popular tourist attraction in Michigan, and has inspired a "Humongous Fungus Fest" held annually in August in Crystal Falls.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] The organism was the subject of a Late Show Top Ten List on Late Night with David Letterman, and an advertising campaign by the rental company U-Haul.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] The life cycle of *A. gallica* includes two diploidization–haploidization events.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] The first of these is the usual process of cell fusion (forming a diploid) followed by meiosis during the formation of haploid basidiospores.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] The second event is more cryptic and occurs before fruit body formation.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] In most basidiomycetous fungi, the hyphae of compatible mating types will fuse to form a two-nucleate, or dikaryotic stage; this stage is not observed in *Armillaria* species, which have cells that are mostly monokaryotic and diploid.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] Genetic analyses suggest that the dikaryotic mycelia undergo an extra haploidization event prior to fruit body formation to create a genetic mosaic.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] These regular and repeating haploidization events result in increased genetic diversity, which helps the fungus to adapt to unfavorable changes in environmental conditions, such as drought.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] The growth rate of *A. gallica* rhizomorphs is between 0.3 and 0.6 m (1.0 and 2.0 ft) per year.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] Population genetic studies of the fungus conducted in the 1990s demonstrated that genetic individuals grow mitotically from a single point of origin to eventually occupy territories that may include many adjacent root systems over large areas (several hectares) of forest floor.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] Based on the low mutation rates observed in large, long-lived individuals, *A. gallica* appears to have an especially stable genome.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] It has also been hypothesized that genetic stability may result from self-renewing mycelial repositories of nuclei with stem cell-like properties.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] Specific mechanisms of somatic growth have been proposed to explain how species such as *A. gallica* keep somatic mutations in check, thus promoting their longevity.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] The common element of these mechanisms is asymmetric cell division in which a group of cells is maintained that divide infrequently and are thus less prone to replication errors leading to mutations.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] At the somatic growth front of *A. gallica* mutation rate was proposed to be kept low by cells dividing infrequently, but giving rise to cells behind the growth front that divide rapidly thus promoting tissue growth although at the expense of a higher mutation rate.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] In North America, it is common east of the Rocky Mountains, but rare in the Pacific Northwest.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] It was found to be the most common *Armillaria* species in hardwood and mixed oak forests in western Massachusetts.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] A Chinese study published in 2001 used the molecular biological technique restriction fragment length polymorphism to analyze the differences in DNA sequence between 23 *A. gallica* specimens collected from the Northern Hemisphere.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] The results suggest that based on the restriction fragment length polymorphism patterns observed, there are four global *A. gallica* subpopulations: the Chinese, European, North American–Chinese, and North American–European geographical lineages.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-lutea] A 2007 study on the northeastern and southwestern Chinese distribution of *Armillaria*, using fruit body and pure culture morphology, concluded that there are several unnamed species (Chinese biological species C, F, H, J and L) that are similar to the common *A. gallica*.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The mushroom is widely distributed in temperate regions of the Northern Hemisphere, usually in heavy soils with temperatures under 79 °F (26 °C).
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] It typically grows on hardwoods but may be found around and on living and dead wood or in open areas.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The species was originally named *Agaricus melleus* by Danish-Norwegian botanist Martin Vahl in 1790; it was transferred to the genus *Armillaria* in 1871 by Paul Kummer.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The basidiocarp of each has a smooth cap 3 to 15 cm (1 to 6 in) in diameter, convex at first but becoming flattened with age often with a central raised umbo, later becoming somewhat dish-shaped.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The margins of the cap are often arched at maturity and the surface is sticky when wet.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Though typically honey-coloured, this fungus is rather variable in appearance and sometimes has a few dark, hairy scales near the centre somewhat radially arranged.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The gills are white at first, sometimes becoming pinkish-yellow or discoloured with age, broad and fairly distant, attached to the stipe at right angles or are slightly decurrent.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The flesh of the cap is whitish and has a sweetish odour and flavour with a tinge of bitterness.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] It is fibrillose and of a firm spongy consistency at first but later becomes hollow.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] It is cylindrical and tapers to a point at its base where it is fused to the stipes of other mushrooms in the clump.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] It is whitish at the upper end and brownish-yellow below, often with a very dark-coloured base.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] There is a broad persistent skin-like ring attached to the upper part of the stipe.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] This has a velvety margin and yellowish fluff underneath and extends outwards as a white partial veil protecting the gills when young.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Under the microscope, the spores are approximately elliptical, 6–9 by 5–7 μm, inamyloid with prominent apiculi (short, pointed projections) at the base.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The basidia (spore-producing structures) lack basal clamps.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The main part of the fungus is underground where a mat of mycelial threads may extend for great distances.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] They are bundled together in rhizomorphs that are black in this species.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The fungal body is not bioluminescent but its mycelia are luminous when in active growth.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] This phenomenon results from a blockage that inhibits the synthesis of hispidin, the precursor to luciferin, as well as 3-hydroxyhispidin hydroxylase in the mushrooms.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] In addition to a number of reclassified species, *Armillaria gemina* lacks the yellow cap background and *A. nabsnona* has a darker hue.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] There are few signs, and they are often difficult to observe.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The most prominent sign is honey-coloured mushrooms at the base of the infected plant.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Additional signs include white, fan-shaped mycelia and black rhizomorphs with diameters between 1⁄32 and 1⁄8 inch (0.8 and 3.2 mm).
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] These usually are not as noticeable because they occur beneath the bark and in the soil, respectively.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Rhizomorphs and mycelial fans are more reliable indicators of *Armillaria* because the mushrooms can be easily mistaken for those of other species.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Additionally, the mushrooms are not consistently present and, when they do occur, remain for only short durations.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The symptoms are much more numerous, including slower growth, dieback of branches, yellowing foliage, rotted wood at base and/or roots, external cankers, cracking bark, bleeding stem, leaf wilting, defoliation, and rapid death.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Leaf wilting, defoliation, and dieback occur after the destruction of the cambium.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Symptoms typically develop gradually, resulting in increased dieback and a reduction in yield as the disease progresses.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] It is one of the most common causes of death in trees and shrubs in both natural and cultivated habitats, and cause steady and substantial losses.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Trees become infected when rhizomorphs growing through the soil encounter uninfected roots.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Alternatively, when infected roots come into contact with uninfected ones the fungal mycelium may grow across.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The rhizomorphs invade the trunk, growing between the bark and the wood and causing wood decay, growth reduction and mortality.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Trees that are already under stress are more likely to be attacked but healthy trees may also be parasitized.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] When rhizomorphs encounter a new, healthy host, mycelium grows over the surface of the roots.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The host may remain asymptomatic for a period; however, under stress conditions, the fungus rapidly penetrates the bark and induces disease.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The foliage becomes sparse and discoloured, twig growth slows down and branches may die back.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] When they are attacked, the Douglas-fir, western larch and some other conifers often produce an extra large crop of cones shortly before dying.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Coniferous trees also tend to ooze resin from infected areas, which often become encrusted with resin, soil, and occasionally fungal tissue.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Whereas broad-leaved trees sometimes develop sunken cankers covered with loose bark that can contain gum or other exudates.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] A growth of fruiting bodies near the base of the trunk confirms the suspicion of Armillaria root rot.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] In 1893, the American mycologist Charles Horton Peck reported finding *Armillaria* fruiting bodies that were "aborted", in a similar way to specimens of *Entoloma abortivum*.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] It was not until 1974 that Roy Watling showed that the aborted specimens included cells of both *Armillaria mellea* and *Entoloma abortivum*.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] He thought that the *Armillaria* was parasitizing the *Entoloma*, a plausible hypothesis given its pathogenic behaviour.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] However, a 2001 study by Czederpiltz, Volk and Burdsall showed that the *Entoloma* was in fact the microparasite.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The whitish-grey malformed fruit bodies known as carpophoroids were the result of *E. abortivum* hyphae penetrating the *Armillaria* and disrupting its normal development.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The rhizomorphs of are initiated from mycelium into multicellular apices of rhizomorphs, which are multicellular vegetative organs that exclude soil from the interior of the rhizomorph tissues.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The rhizomorphs spread through far greater distances through the ground than the mycelium.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The rhizomorphs are black in this species.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The fungal body is not bioluminescent but its mycelia and rhizomorphs are luminous when in active growth.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] *A. mellea* producing rhizomorphs is parasitic on woody plants of many species, including especially shrubs, hardwood and evergreen trees.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] In one example, *A. mellea* spread by rhizomorphs from an initially infected tree killed 600 trees in a prune orchard in 6 years.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Each infected tree was immediately adjacent to an already infected one, the spread by rhizomorphs through the tree roots and soil.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] There are fungicides or management practices that will kill *A. mellea* after infection without damaging the infected plant, but these practices are still being studied.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] There are practices that can extend the life of the plant and prevent further spreading.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The best way to extend the plant life is to improve the host condition through supplemental watering and fertilization.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] There is also some evidence that biological control using the fungus genus *Trichoderma* may help.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] *Trichoderma* is a predator of *A. mellea* and is often found in woodchips.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Therefore, chipping or grinding dead and infected roots will give *Trichoderma* its preferred habitat and help it proliferate.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Armillaria root rot frequently causes fatal outcomes in grapevines.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The pathogen infects the roots and root crown, destroying the cambium layer and decaying xylem tissue, which results in white rot.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The presence of rhizomorphs and mycelial fans is a more reliable indicator of *Armillaria* infection than mushrooms, since mushrooms can be confused with other species, may not appear annually, and are present only briefly.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Grapevines infected with *Armillaria* *mellea* often display shriveled berries.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Rapid desiccation of leaves and berries, followed by vine death after veraison and before harvest, may occur in plants that previously showed moderate symptoms.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Outbreaks in vineyards typically begin at a single infection point and expand outward in a circular pattern.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Grapevines at the center of the infection exhibit more severe symptoms or die more rapidly than those at the periphery, which may remain asymptomatic.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Infection often occurs through contact with previously infected woody material in the soil, especially in areas formerly occupied by Quercus species, as the fungus can persist as mycelium for years within woody debris.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The fungus persists on both living and dead grapevine root tissues, which facilitates its spread and accelerates plant degradation under environmental stress.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Severely stunted shoots that are not killed by the disease rarely survive through dormancy and budbreak.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Grapevines typically die when approximately half of the root collar has been girdled, impeding adequate water transport.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Although several *Armillaria* species can cause the disease, most infections are attributed to *A. mellea*, which is currently the only known species to kill grapevines, although this may be due to ongoing challenges in the taxonomy of *Armillaria* species.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Cultivation of *A. mellea* started with cultivation of its mycellia, which is used to support the cultivation of *Gastrodia elata*, a non-photosynthetic species of orchid used in traditional Chinese medicine.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] This kind of cultivation has been present since 1994 and uses pieces of wood inoculated with the fungus.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] In 2017, farmers from Heilongjiang succeeded in producing fruiting bodies (mushrooms) through cultivation.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Two methods were possible, one using wood pieces, the other using bagged media.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] By 2019, the spent myceliated wood from *Gastrodia* cultivation is routinely used to seed new wood for mushroom production.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The mushrooms have a taste that has been described as slightly sweet and nutty, with a texture ranging from chewy to crunchy, depending on the method of preparation.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Parboiling mushrooms before consuming removes the bitter taste present in some specimens and may reduce the amount of gastrointestinal irritants.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] According to one guide, they must be cooked before eating.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Drying the mushrooms preserves and intensifies their flavour, although reconstituted mushrooms tend to be tough to eat.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The mushrooms can also be pickled and roasted.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Different nutritional parameters of *A. mellea*, like protein, carbohydrate, fat, amino acid and crude have been studied.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The fruit body contains large amounts of carbohydrates including polysaccharides such as glucans and glycogen, monosaccharides and disaccharides (such as trehalose), sugar, alcohols (such as manitol) and chitin.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The mushroom is rich in protein and carbohydrate but is low amount of fat which could serve a proper diet for persons who sufferer from hypertension and atherosclerosis.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Furthermore, due to the presence of high level of crude fiber it could help to control diabetes and obesity.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The mushrooms also may have been used medicinally by indigenous peoples as a laxative.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Several bioactive compounds have been isolated and identified from the fruit bodies.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The triterpenes 3β-hydroxyglutin-5-ene, friedelane-2α,3β-diol, and friedelin were reported in 2011.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Indole compounds include tryptamine, L-tryptophan and serotonin.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] The fungus produces cytotoxic compounds known as melleolides.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Melleolides are made from orsellinic acid and protoilludane sesquiterpene alcohols via esterification.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] A polyketide synthase gene, termed *ArmB*, was identified in the genome of the fungus, which was found expressed during melleolide production.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] 42% similarity with the orsellinic acid synthase gene (*OrsA*) in *Aspergillus nidulans*.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Characterization of the gene proved it to catalyze orsillinic acid in vitro.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] It is a non-reducing iterative type-1 polyketide synthase.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Co-incubation of free orsellinic acid with alcohols and ArmB showed cross-coupling activity.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Therefore, the enzyme has transesterification activity.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Other auxiliary factors are suspected to control substrate specificity.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Additionally, halogen modifications have been observed.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] Overexpression of annotated halogenases (termed *ArmH1-5*) and characterization of the subsequent enzymes revealed in all five enzymes the chlorination of mellolide F.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria-mellea] In vitro reactions of free-standing substrates showed that the enzymes do not require auxiliary carrier proteins for substrate delivery.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] The name *Armillaria* was defined in 1821 by Elias Magnus Fries, but at that time most gilled mushrooms were considered to belong to genus *Agaricus* and *Armillaria* was only a subgenus (a "tribe").
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] In 1857, Friedrich Staude established the independent genus.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] Similar lists of biological species have been constructed by mycologists working in Japan (10 as of 1998) and China (16 as of 2024).
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] Further data from molecular diagnostic tools have removed much uncertainty for mycologists and forest pathologists.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] New questions remain unanswered regarding the phylogeny of North American *Armillaria* species and their relationships to their European counterparts, particularly within the "*Armillaria mellea* complex".
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] Some data suggest that North American and European *A. gallica* isolates are not monophyletic.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] Although North American and European isolates of *A. gallica* may be interfertile, some North American isolates of *A. gallica* are more closely related to the North American taxon *A. calvescens* than to European isolates of *A. gallica*.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] The increase in genetic divergence has not necessarily barred inter-sterility between isolated populations of *A. gallica*.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] Although the relationships among some groups in the genus seem clearer, the investigation of geographically diverse isolates has revealed that the relationship between some North American species is still unclear (Hughes et al.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] A similar situation happens in China, where some molecular phylogenetic data appear to line up with intersterile "biological species" and others do not.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] In 1791 Albrecht Wilhelm Roth described the species *Rhizomorpha fragilis* for a collection which consisted entirely of rhizomorphs.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] The genus *Rhizomorpha* thus became established and later these mycelial cords were shown to belong to *Armillaria mellea*.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] According to the code of nomenclature that means that the two genus names are synonyms and since genus *Armillaria* was not defined until 1857, the name *Rhizomorpha* takes precedence and should replace the name *Armillaria*.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] To avoid this, a 2021 paper by Stalpers et al. proposes that the name *Armillaria* should be protected.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] The proposal awaits decisions by the Nomenclature Committee for Fungi and eventually by an International Botanical Congress.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] The basidiocarp (reproductive structure) of the fungus is a mushroom that grows on wood, typically in small dense clumps or tufts.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] Their caps (mushroom tops) are typically yellow-brown, somewhat sticky to touch when moist, and, depending on age, may range in shape from conical to convex to depressed in the center.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] The stipe (stalk) may or may not have a ring.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] All *Armillaria* species have a white spore print and none have a volva (cup at base).
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] Similar species include *Pholiota* spp. which also grow in cespitose (mat-like) clusters on wood and fruit in the fall.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] *Pholiota* spp. are separated from Armillaria by its yellowish to greenish-yellow tone and a dark brown to grey-brown spore print.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] Mushroom hunters need to be wary of *Galerina* spp. which can grow side by side with *Armillaria* spp. on wood.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] *Galerina* have a dark brown spore print and are deadly poisonous (alpha-amanitin).
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] The white spore print and lack of volva can be compared to *Amanita*.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] As a white rot, it is distinguished from *Tricholoma*, a mycorrhizal (non-parasitic) genus.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] Honey fungus is a white-rot fungus, which is a pathogenic organism that affects trees, shrubs, woody climbers and rarely, woody herbaceous perennial plants.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] Honey fungus can grow on living, decaying, and also dead plant material (being a facultative saprophyte).
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] This means it can kill its host with little consequence, unlike parasites that must moderate their growth to avoid host death.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] Honey fungus spreads from living trees, dead and live roots and stumps by means of reddish-brown to black rhizomorphs (root-like structures) at the rate of approximately 3.3 feet (1 m) a year, but infection by root contact is possible.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] Rhizomorphs grow close to the soil surface (in the top 7.9 inches (20 cm)) and invade new roots, or the root collar (where the roots meet the stem) of plants.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] An infected tree will die once the fungus has girdled it, or when significant root damage has occurred.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] Additionally, Infections can occur through the activity of wood boring beetles.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] For example, *Agrilus biguttatus* most commonly girdle in oak trees, which allows fungi to grow in the stems of these infected trees.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] This can happen rapidly, or may take several years.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] Infected plants will deteriorate, although may exhibit prolific flower or fruit production shortly before death.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] Initial symptoms of honey fungus infection include dieback or shortage of leaves in spring.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] Rhizomorphs (also called mycelial cords) appear under the bark and around the tree, and mushrooms grow in clusters from the infected plant in autumn and die back after the first frost.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] However these symptoms and signs do not necessarily mean that the pathogenic strains of honey fungus are the cause, so other identification methods are advised before diagnosis.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] Thin sheets of cream colored mycelium, beneath the bark at the base of the trunk or stem indicated that honey fungus is likely the pathogen.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] It will give off a strong mushroom scent and the mushrooms sometimes extend upward.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] On conifers honey fungus often exudes a gum or resin from cracks in the bark.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] Potential hosts include conifers and various monocotyledonous and dicotyledonous trees, shrubs, and herbaceous species, ranging from asparagus and strawberry to large forest trees (Patton and Vasquez Bravo 1967).
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] *Armillaria* root rot enters hosts through the roots.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] In Alberta, 75% of trap logs (Mallett and Hiratsuka 1985) inserted into the soil between planted spruce became infected with the distinctive white mycelium of *Armillaria* within one year.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] Of the infestations, 12% were *A. ostoyae*, and 88% were *A. sinapina* (Blenis et al.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] Reviews of the biology, diversity, pathology, and control of *Armillaria* in Fox (2000) are useful.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] Honey fungus are regarded in Ukraine, Russia, Poland, Germany and other European countries as one of the best wild mushrooms.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] They are commonly ranked above morels and chanterelles and only the cep/porcini is more highly prized.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] However, honey fungus must be thoroughly cooked as they are mildly poisonous raw.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] Honey mushrooms are one of four UK species that can cause sickness when ingested with alcohol.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] For those unfamiliar with the species, it is advisable not to drink alcohol for 12 hours before and 24 hours after eating this mushroom to avoid any possible nausea and vomiting.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] However, if these rules are followed, this variety of mushroom is a delicacy with a distinctive mushroomy and nutty flavour.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] Reference texts for identification are *Collins Complete British Mushrooms and Toadstools* for the variety of field pictures in it, and Roger Philips' *Mushrooms* for the quality of his out of field pictures and descriptions.
[src:armillaria-mellea/armillaria] In Norway, some mycologists have started to regard honey fungus as poisonous, as the Norwegian health ministry is moving away from the parboiling practice.
